course.course_desc: Introduction to Computer Science. This course provides an overview of the fundamental concepts and principles of computer science
Calculus I. This course covers topics such as limits, derivatives, and integrals, with an emphasis on applications in various fields
Art History. Explore the major art movements and styles throughout history, from ancient civilizations to the modern era
Organic Chemistry. Study the structure, properties, composition, reactions, and synthesis of organic compounds
Introduction to Psychology. Learn about the basic principles and theories of psychology, including human behavior and mental processes
World Literature. Dive into the works of renowned authors from different cultures and time periods, analyzing their themes and styles
Microeconomics. Understand the principles of individual economic decision-making, market structures, and the role of government
Introduction to Sociology. Examine the social structures, institutions, and processes that shape human behavior and society
Environmental Science. Explore the interrelationships between humans and the environment, and study environmental issues and solutions
Introduction to Philosophy. Delve into the fundamental questions about existence, knowledge, ethics, and the nature of reality
Statistics. Learn the techniques for collecting, analyzing, and interpreting data, and apply statistical methods to real-world problems
American History. Study the major events, figures, and themes in American history from the colonial period to the present day
Introduction to Marketing. Gain an understanding of marketing principles, consumer behavior, market research, and marketing strategies
Introduction to Anthropology. Explore the study of human societies, cultures, and biological diversity across time and space
Macroeconomics. Analyze the economy as a whole, including topics such as economic growth, inflation, and fiscal policy
Introduction to Linguistics. Study the scientific study of language, including its structure, sounds, meaning, and social aspects
Introduction to Political Science. Examine the theories, institutions, and processes of politics and government
Physical Geology. Learn about the Earth's materials, processes, and structures, including rocks, minerals, and plate tectonics
Introduction to Film Studies. Analyze the art and history of cinema, exploring film genres, techniques, and cultural impact
Introduction to Astronomy. Explore the universe, including the solar system, stars, galaxies, and the Big Bang theory
Introduction to Ethics. Examine ethical theories and principles, and apply them to contemporary moral issues
Introduction to Communication Studies. Study the theories and practices of human communication in various contexts
Introduction to Archaeology. Learn about the methods and techniques used to uncover and interpret past human cultures
Introduction to Music Theory. Study the fundamentals of music notation, harmony, rhythm, and musical analysis
Introduction to International Relations. Analyze the relationships between nations, global issues, and international organizations
Introduction to Gender Studies. Explore the social construction of gender, gender identity, and gender inequality
Introduction to Theater Arts. Learn about the history, theory, and practice of theater, including acting and production
Introduction to Public Health. Study the principles and practices of promoting and protecting the health of populations
Introduction to Creative Writing. Develop your writing skills and explore various genres, such as fiction, poetry, and non-fiction
Introduction to Human Anatomy. Study the structure and function of the human body, including organs, tissues, and systems.
